{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_goldman_ver01/data/sn82015313/00383349242/1930022201/0088.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE 8\nPolar QUALITY Refrigerators\nYou can not buy a poor refrigerator from Polar.\nWe will not sell them.\nREFRIGERATOR SALESROOM AT 2000 NORTHWESTERN AVE.\nPOLAR ICE AND FUEL CO.\nA New Appearance for Your Car\nA Duco job will do wonders\u2014in making the old boat look like\nnew. The cost is inconsiderable\u2014the result surprising.\nHARE CHEVROLET COMPANY\n552 East Washington St. Phone Riley 5325\nIndiana\u2019s Finest Transient and Apartment Hotel\nThe refined\natmosphere\nof home!\nPhone\nLincoln 2361\nOVERLOOKING MERIDIAN PLAZA\nSPINK ARMS HOTEL\nComplete Factory\nMaintenance\n6 Departments\nUnder One Roof\nLIGHT MACHINE SHOP\nHEAVY MACHINE SHOP\nHOI I KK SHOP\nBLACKSMITH SHOP\nKOINHRY\nWOOD-WORKING SHOP\n1 Management\nOverhead\nThe SINKER-DAVIS Cos.\n230 S. Missouri\nPhone, LI. 3559\nIndiana Automatic Sprinkler Cos. i\nFire Prevention\nLin. 9540 j\n-JAuto\u00dfody\nRepaipihc\nand\nFender Repairing\nDone by experts, whose years of\nexperience assure you of results that\nwill more than please.\nC. Off and Company\n107 N. East St LL 1549\nSewer Construction of All Types\nCall Us for Estimates\nCOLUMBIA CONSTRUCTION CO.\n2108 Columbia Ave. HE mlock 4566\nAuto Glass\n\u2018Duplicate shatter-proof safety Klass'\n\u2018installed while you wait.\nDistributors:\nFrancisco Auto Heaters\nRusco Brake Lining\nPerfection Windshield\nCompany\n[zs W*. Pratt St. Lincoln S(MO'\nJoseph Gardner I\nCompany\nTin, Copper and\nSheet Iron Work\nRepair* on Slate, Tile and Gravel\nRoofs, Gutters. SpoutinK and\nFurnaces\nRiley 1562\n147-153 KENTUCKY AVENUE\nOTJPL VIEWS\nINDIANAPOLIS PROGRESS\nTwo essential features for efficient\nrefrigeration are: First, top, back,\nbottom, ends and all doors, should\nbe lined with cork board, wrapped\nin water-proof paper, which forms\nthe best insulation known. Sec\nond, rubber gaskets on all doors\neliminate heat leakage and in\nsure tight fitting doors.\nThese features are combined in\nall Polar refrigerators.\n\u2014Colorful\nROOFS!\n\u2014always are pleasing and at\ntractive. We are roofing spe\ncialists and will gladly furnish\nestimates nnd advise you on\nyour roofing needs.\nHenry C. Smither\nRoofing Cos.\n430 S. Meridian Llntoln 4937\nAll Expense\nCruise De Luxe\nMediterranean\nThe most comprehensive Itiner\nary of romantic and historic\ncities offering an excep\ntionally lon* visit In Egypt and\nthe Holy Eand and in\ncluding such unusual ports a#\nCattaro. Tunis, Malta, Syracuse.\nTaormina, Ragusa in ad\ndition to the usual Mediterran\nean countries.\nFor Further Information\nThe Union Trust Cos.\nRichard A. Kurts, Travel Dept, Mgr.\nMarietta Mfg.\nCompany\n16th St and Sherman Drive\nIndianapolis\nCan-omtx\nf :(>vous. S\\urbLe\nCHROME\nPLATING\nNICKEL. COPPER OXJD\nAND\nPOLISHING OF ALL METALS\nThe ADAMS PLATING\nCOMPANY\n\u201cThe Service Platers\u201d\nLincoln 8*97 IS* W. lOtb St.\nWe Furnish Truck service\nUNION TRACTION\nGIVES SHIPPERS\nFREE CARTAGE\nLine Arranges to Absorb\nCost of Delivery and\nPick-up Service.\nArrangements having the effect\nof giving freight and express ship\npers benefit of pickup or delivery\nservice at tnelr doors will be placed\nin effect Monday, Feb. 24, at\ntwenty-three principal stations of\nthe Union Traction lines.\nUnder this arrangement, the\nUnion Traction Company and con\nnecting electric railways will, under\ncertain conditions, refund or absorb\nthe expense of trucking freight and\nexpress between the freight houses\nand the shippers\u2019 places of business,\naccording to F. D. Norviel, general\npassenger and freight agent.\nShippers, to secure this benefit,\nare required to furnish certain mini\nmum tonnages of freight, depending\non its classification, and ranging\nfrom 2,500 to 10,000 pounds or more.\nEmployes Added\nThe Union Traction Company is\nmaking extensive preparations to in\nform shippers of the new arrange\nments and to handle the very con\nsiderable increase in tonnage which\nwill result. It is expected addi\ntional employes will be needed at\nthe local freight house and other\nfacilities will be made necessary,\nNorviel said.\nUnion Traction lines, north and\neast from Indianapolis, have been\na favorite route for shippers of\nfreight and express, not only to\npoints reached by the lines, but to\npoints hundreds of miles beyond,\nreached by connecting electrical\nrailways and truck lines, with which\nthrough rates are in effect, Norviel\nsaid.\nThe new arrangement is provided\nto make it more profitable and de\nsirable for shippers to use this fast\nconvenient route. Freight ship\nments may be brought to the main\nfreight house on Kentucky avenue,\nor to the north side freight house,\nNineteenth and Martindale avenue,\nunder the new arrangements.\nReceive Shipments\nInformation concerning the serv\nice may be obtained from P. L.\nJoyce, local division passenger and\nfreight agent, or from Gaven\nStuart, general agent for the com\npany, at the Indianapolis freight\nhouse, or upon written inquiry ad\ndressed to the traffic department at\nAnderson, Ind.\nPassenger business of the com\npany has held up surprisingly well\nunder the recent business condi\ntions, Norviel said, due largely to\npopularity of the 500 penny coupon\nbooks, sold for $4, the low week\nend excursion fares to hundreds of\npoints and to the convenience of\nthe passenger transportation service\nmaintained by the Union Traction\nCompany.\nj:;HOT f\nTrrtrC'v. A\nf-ifcLnot- n\nFOOL THE SUM\"\nR.)y77 22\nINDIANAPOLIS\nTENT AWN INC\nStreet and Road\nPaving\nIndiana\nAsphalt Paving\nCompany\n(Incorporated)\n28th Street and\nColumbia Avenue\nPhone\u2014llEmlock 3545\nResidence Phone HE. 5615\nA. C. JOHNSON\nBRICK CONTRACTOR\n845 Massachusetts Ave.\nPhone, Riley 2452\nCHARLES McGARVEY\nPLASTERING CONTRACTOR\nESTABLISHED 1893\n5264 Washington Blvd. Phone Humboldt 4582\nStrathmann Construction Cos.\nGENERAL CONTRACTORS-ENGINEERS\n839 Architects and Builders Bldg.\nTel. Riley 8512\nTHE INDIANAPOLIS TIMES\nMOISTURE IN FOOD\nCONSERVED BY ICE\nArtificial Product Retains\nFull Value of Meats\nand Vegetables.\nThe Artificial Ice and Cold Stor\nage Company is preparing for a\nlarger season this year than any in\nthe past.\nConsumption of ice per individual\nhas increased materially in the past\nten years as more and more per\nsons are realizing the necessity of\nrefrigeration in preserving food.\nBoxes refrigerated with artificial\nice always keep food wholesome and\nfree from odors, besides maintaining\nthe natural moisture, according to\nManager A. C. Goll.\nFood refrigerated with artificial\nice can be kept for any length of\ntime without any depreciable loss\nof moisture. Health and happiness,\nSeveral Houses Sold\nby Realtors in City\nPart of Baldwin Building\nLeased to Local Firm\nfor Four Years.\nConsummation of several residen\ntial deals were announced this week\nby Indianapolis realtors.\nRobert Allison of the Allison\nCLEAN STORAGE\nOFFEREDPUBLIC\nLocal Warehouse Provides\nindividual Lockers.\nSafe and clean storage for furni\nture in one of the largest and most\nmodern warehouses in the state is\noffered the public by the Shank\nFireproof Storage Company, 1430\nNorth Illinois street.\nCleanliness is assured by thor\nough fumigation and cleansing of\nall storage departments each week.\nSpecial storage rooms, steam heated\nand offering even temperature at\nall times, are provided for pianos.\nAnother feature of the service is\nthe individual locker service for\nthose wishing it. A vault is pro\nvided for oriental rugs with a spe\ncially made tear gas burglar-prcof\ndoor. A lock box vault is provided\non the first floor.\nThe Shank company is equipped\nto pack furniture for shipment any\ndistance. Dead storage is provided\nfor automobiles.\nThe storage company was founded\nabout thirty-five years ago by the\nlate Lew Shank, former mayor, first,\nbeing located on East Washington\nstreet. The present commodious,\nmodern building was constructed on\nIllinois street about three years ago.\nSince the death of Mr. Shank,\nthe business has been carried on\nby Mrs. Shank, just as it was con\nducted by the former mayor, with\nhis policy of courtesy and fail\ndealings.\nBurt I.* I\nIoA\nI SjC UI S .r }j ,J*\nOr. S7> f f es\nOstermeyer Paper Cos.\nRiley 6902 148 Virginia Ave.\nm\n500-\nMile Race\nAN\nINDIANAPOLIS\nINSTITUTION\n(\u2022he said, are the greatest assets of\nmankind, and these are maintained\nonly by proper food preservation.\nMeats and vegetables maintain\ntheir full food values when pre\nserved with artificial ice, he added.\nThe Artificial Ice and Cold\nStorage is centrally located and\nwith its modern equipment is able\nto deliver ice on short notice to any\npart of the city.\nThe company maintains a large\nnumber of stations in the outlying\ndistricts of the city in order to pro\nvide the best possible service for its\npatrons.\nIce manufactured by the company\nis made of water continuously agi\ntated by means of air under com\npression while it is being frozen.\nThis insures ice free from contami\nnation as impurities are confined\nto the small core which is pumped\nout and refilled with pure water be\nfore the cake is completely frozen.\nRealty Company, announced sale of\na building contract for a five-room\nbrick veneer bungalow, to be built\non the corner of Manker and\nSouthern avenues, to Catherine C.\nBowers. The Allison company sold\na five-room, modern English type\nhome at 913 Yoke street, to George\nand Selma Wuellner, and a five\nroom modern bungalow at 6456\nPark avenue to William White.\nThe Allison company aiso an\nnounced sale of a four-room semi\nmodern house at 2636 Olney ave\nnue to Emily P. Miller, by David T.\nNicoson, and sale of a five-room\nmodern frame bungalow at 2725\nBarth avenue in the Garfield park\nsection, to Robert Robbins, by\nRobert Allison and T. E. Grinslade.\nThe Grinslade Construction Com\npany sold a five-room modern\nbungalow at 2534 South East street\nto Norman Werts, and a five-room\nmodern bungalow at 2522 South\nEast street, to Chester Brooks. C.\nO, Grinslade sold a five-room\nmodern frame bungalow at 3932\nEast Eleventh street, to John E.\nMerl.\nCarl G. Seytter, 225 Lemcke\nbuilding, announced sale of a five\nroom modern bungalow at 1312\nNorth Euclid avenue owned by E.\nB. Palmer, to Carrie M. Hartman.\nA four-year lease was consum\nmated between Edward G. Hereth,\net al, and the Paramount Optical\nCompany, which leased part of the\nthird floor of the Baldwin building\nfor a four year period, at a yearly\nconsideration of $2,007.\nPERMIT TOTAL $109,599\nSteady Rise in Building Shown for\nCity Since First of Year.\nBuilding permits issued in Indi\nanapolis this week totaled $109,599,\nindicating a steacry rise in building\nfigures since the first of the year,\naccording to compilations made by\nthe Indianapolis Real Estate Board.\nFifteen dwellings, two store rooms,\none garage building, and three fill\ning stations are among the larger\nprojects included.\nColumbus Man Dies\nPH Timex ftnecial\nCOLUMBUS. Ind., Feb. 22.\u2014D. E.\nRiley, 75, died here following a four\nweeks\u2019 illness. He was a retired\nemploye of the B. O. railroad.\nt Knows!\nGOOD\nLUMBER\nThe veteran carpen\nter through his years\nof handling Lumber\nfrom Brannum*\nKeene Lumber Cos.\ninvariably knows that\nonly quality materials\ncome from us. Previ\nous to delivery every\npiece undergoes rigid\ninspection, thus as\nsuring you that our\nLumber measures up\nto specifications.\nBrannum-Keene\nLumber Cos.\nPhone, Irvington 04C4\n3506 E. Washington\nRELIABLE FREIGHT SERVICE\ntw -VIA\nTERRE HAUTE, HiDIAHAPOUS\nEASTERN TRACTKHi CO.\nOvernight delivery on L. C. L. and carload shipments\nto all Local and many Interline points.\nDispatch Freight Carried on All Passenger Cars.\nUse Our Service and Be Convinced\nSPRING PLATING\nRUSH STARTED\nMUCH EARLIER\nDemand for Chrome Finish\non Automobiles Shows\nLarge Increase.\nThe spring rush for plating work\nhas started two months earlier this\nyear than usual, according to Al\nbert P. Kriese, production manager\nof Adams Plating Company, 138\nWest Tenth street.\nOrdinarily, December, January\nFebruary and March are dull\nmonths in the plating business but\nthis year business has not slumped\nthese mon hs, Kriese said.\nThe Adams Platine Company\nI has been forced to maintain a night\nforce on the job almost continu\nously since Jan. 1. From present\nconditions, the business outlook for\nthis year is excellent, he added.\nFinish Beautiful\nA large proportion of the com\npany\u2019s work at this time is the plat\ning of automobile parts, including\nheadlights, bumpers, radiator shells,\nhub caps, door handies and other\nnickeled parts.\nDemand is principally for chrome\nplating, Kriese said, because of its\nbeautiful, enduring and non-tar\nnishing finish, although the firm\nalso handles nickel plating work.\nChromium plating is the latest\ndevelopment in the plating indus\ntry. Many automobile manufac\nturers now' chrome plate their cars\nat the factory.\nBuild Up Business\nHundreds of owners of cars pur\nchased before the factories adopted\nthe new finish, are taking their\nradiator shells, head lights and\nbumpers to the Adams Plating\nCompany for chrome plating.\nThe firm w'as organized ten years\nago by Thomas, Robert and Ed\nward Adams, the present owners,\nwho by taking an active part in\noperation of the plant, insure high\nest efficiency and quality work at a\nreasonable price. Starting with\nnothing, they have built up a\n$70,000 annual business.\nClinton Man Kills Seif\nBy United Press\nCLINTON, Ind., Feb. 22. John\nJones, 68, committed suicide in his\nhome here by shooting. Friends said\nill health probably was the cause.\nHe placed a shotgun against his\nside and pulled the trigger with a\npoker.\nFor Those Who\nPrefer a Finer\nCOFFEE\nIn the New Seal-Packed Can\nINDIANAPOLIS MADE\nfor Central Indiana People\nSold 